# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: córdoba-argentina
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:córdoba-argentina/1967-basketball-world-cup] The **1967 FIBA World Championship** was the 5th FIBA World Championship, the international basketball world championship for men's national teams.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1967-basketball-world-cup] It was hosted by Montevideo, Uruguay from 27 May to 11 June 1967.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1967-basketball-world-cup] Rules for classification: 1) points; 2) head-to-head points; 3) head-to-head goal average; 4) head-to-head number of points scored.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The **1978 FIFA World Cup** was the 11th edition of the FIFA World Cup, the quadrennial international football world championship tournament among the men's senior national teams.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] It was held in Argentina between 1 and 25 June.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The Cup was won by the host nation, Argentina, who defeated the Netherlands 3–1 in the final, after extra time.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The final was held at River Plate's home stadium, Estadio Monumental, in the Argentine capital of Buenos Aires.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] This win was the first World Cup title for Argentina, who became the fifth team (after Uruguay, Italy, England, and West Germany) to be both hosts and world champions and the third South American team to win the World Cup.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Argentina, the Netherlands, and Brazil were the gold, silver, and bronze medalists, respectively.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Iran and Tunisia made their first appearances in the tournament.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The defending champions, West Germany, were eliminated in the second round (finishing third in their group).
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] This was also the last World Cup tournament to use the original inclusion of 16 teams.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Since the first World Cup in 1930, only 15 teams (plus the host, who automatically qualified) had been allowed to qualify (the reigning title holders also received automatic qualification from 1934 through 2002); but for the next World Cup, in Spain, FIFA expanded that tournament to 24 teams.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] This tournament was marred by flagrant controversy, domestic politics, and alleged interference and match-fixing by the Argentine authoritarian military junta government that was using this tournament as an opportunity for nationalistic propaganda and for seeking legitimacy on the world stage.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] During the months before the start of the World Cup, the junta was intending to dismantle those who were against them and mitigate criticism from the public on their policies.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The official match ball was the Adidas Tango Durlast.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Argentina was chosen as the host nation by FIFA on 6 July 1966 in London, England, when the hosts for 1974, 1978 and 1982 editions were chosen.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Mexico withdrew from the bidding process after having been awarded the 1970 event two years earlier.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The logo is based on President Juan Perón's signature gesture: a salute to the crowd with both arms extended above his head.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] This was one of the most famous, populist images of Perón.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The design was created in 1974, two years prior to the military coup in 1976.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The military leadership were aware that the World Cup's logo symbolised Perón's gesture, and they tried to change the competition's logo.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] At this point, the design was already broadly commercialised and the merchandise had already been made: a forced modification "would trigger a sea of lawsuits against the country", so the military had no option but to give up their attempts and leave it.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The monetary cost of preparing to host the World Cup was put at $700 million, including building three new stadia and redeveloping three others; building five press centres; a new communications system costing $100 million; and improvements to transport systems.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Newcomers to the finals were Iran and Tunisia; Austria qualified for the first time since 1958, while France, Spain and Hungary were back for the first time since 1966.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Peru and Mexico returned after missing the 1974 tournament.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] For the first time, more than 100 nations entered the competition.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The format of the competition stayed the same as in 1974: 16 teams qualified, divided into four groups of four.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Each group played a round-robin with two points for a win and one for a draw, and goal difference used to separate teams level on points.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The top two teams in each group would advance to the second round, where they would be split into two groups of four.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The winners of each group would play each other in the final, and the second-place finishers in the match for third place.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The first round produced several surprises.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Poland won Group 2 ahead of world champions West Germany, after holding the Germans to a goalless draw and then beating Tunisia and Mexico.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The Germans then beat Mexico 6–0, and finally played out a second goalless draw against Tunisia.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Although they failed to qualify for the second round, Tunisia made history by beating Mexico 3–1 while trailing 0–1 at half time.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] It was the first time that any African team had won a match at the World Cup finals.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Peru pushed the Netherlands into second place in Group 4, where Scotland missed out on goal difference for the second successive tournament.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Teófilo Cubillas was outstanding for Peru, scoring twice against Scotland in Peru's 3–1 win and hitting a hat-trick in their 4–1 victory over newcomers Iran.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Rob Rensenbrink of the Netherlands also scored three times against Iran, scoring all the goals as the Dutch won 3–0.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Scotland drew with Iran 1–1 and the only highlight of their campaign was a 3–2 victory over the Netherlands in their final group game which was not enough to prevent elimination.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Iran, the reigning Asian champions, went out of the tournament winless.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Rensenbrink's goal against Scotland was the 1000th goal of World Cup history.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Scotland's Willie Johnston was expelled from the World Cup after he was found to have taken a banned stimulant during the opening game against Peru.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The biggest surprise of all came in Group 3, where Austria finished ahead of Brazil.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The Austrians beat Spain and Sweden, while Brazil were held to draws by the same two teams.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The draw between Brazil and Sweden was especially controversial; Welsh referee Clive Thomas awarded Brazil a very late corner kick, and Zico directly headed the kick into the net; but Thomas blew for time before Zico made contact with the ball, and the goal was disallowed.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The Brazilian players were not happy with the decision, but the final result remained a 1–1 draw.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Heading into their final group game, Brazil needed to beat Austria to be certain of advancing to the second round and managed a 1–0 win thanks to a goal from Roberto Dinamite.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Brazil and Austria thus finished with the same number of points and the same goal difference, but Austria won the group by virtue of having scored more goals.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Group 1 had the strongest line-up of teams in the first round, featuring Italy, the host Argentina, France and Hungary.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The two places in the second round were claimed before the final round of games, with Italy and Argentina both beating France and Hungary.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The match between Italy and Argentina decided who topped the group, and a goal from Roberto Bettega midway through the second half was enough to give that honour to Italy.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] It also forced Argentina to move out of Buenos Aires and play in Rosario.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The incident happened during the game between France and Hungary.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Both teams arrived at the venue with only their white change kits, resulting in a delayed kickoff while officials went in search of the jerseys of a local team from Mar del Plata, Club Atlético Kimberley; the jerseys had vertical green and white stripes and were worn by France.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] In the all-European Group A, the Netherlands got off to a flying start by thrashing Austria 5–1, Johnny Rep scoring two of their goals.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] In a rematch of the 1974 final, the Dutch then drew 2–2 with West Germany, who had previously shared a goalless game with Italy.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The Italians beat Austria 1–0, and so the Netherlands faced Italy in their last group game knowing that the winners would reach the final.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Ernie Brandts scored an 18th-minute own goal to put Italy ahead at half-time, but he made up for his mistake by scoring at the right end in the fifth minute of the second half.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Arie Haan got the winner for the Dutch with 15 minutes remaining, and the Netherlands had reached their second successive World Cup Final.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] In the game known as the miracle of Cordoba, West Germany were surprisingly beaten by Austria 2–3 which marked their end as World Champions.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Group B was essentially a battle between Argentina and Brazil, and it was resolved in controversial circumstances.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] In the first round of group games, Brazil beat Peru 3–0 while Argentina saw Poland off by a score of 2–0.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Brazil and Argentina then played out a tense and violent goalless draw, so both teams went into the last round of matches with three points.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Argentina delayed the kick-off of its last match to await the result of the Brazil-Poland encounter.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Brazil won by a 3–1 score, meaning Argentina had to beat Peru by four clear goals to reach the final but they managed to do it.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Trailing 2–0 at half-time, Peru simply collapsed in the second half, and Argentina eventually won 6–0.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] As previously noted, rumours suggested that Peru might have been bribed or threatened into allowing Argentina to win the match by such a large margin.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] However, nothing could be proved, and Argentina met the Netherlands in the final.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Brazil took third place from an enterprising Italian side with Nelinho scoring a memorable goal, and were dubbed "moral champions" by coach Cláudio Coutinho, because they did not win the tournament, but did not lose a single match.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The final, Argentina vs Netherlands, was also controversial, as the Dutch accused the Argentines of using stalling tactics to delay the match.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The host team came out late and questioned the legality of a plaster cast on René van de Kerkhof's wrist, which the Dutch said allowed tension to build in front of a hostile Buenos Aires crowd.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Mario Kempes opened the scoring for the hosts before Dick Nanninga equalised a few minutes from the end.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Rob Rensenbrink had a glorious stoppage-time opportunity to win it for the Netherlands but his effort came back off the goal post.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Argentina won the final 3–1 after extra time, after Daniel Bertoni scored and Kempes, who finished as the tournament's top scorer with six goals, added his second of the day.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The Netherlands, because of the controversial game events, refused to attend the post-match ceremonies after the match ended.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] They had lost their second consecutive World Cup final, both times to the host nation, after losing to West Germany in 1974.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Argentina won 5 games but became the first team to win the World Cup after failing to win two matches, where they had lost to Italy in the first round and drawn with Brazil in the second round.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Four years later, Italy would win the next World Cup despite failing to win three games.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The official mascot of this World Cup was *Gauchito*, a boy wearing an Argentina kit.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] His hat (with the words ARGENTINA '78), neckerchief, and whip are typical of gauchos.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] In 1972, eight venues were preselected; six that were used for the finals, plus La Plata and Tucuman.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] La Plata, the city of the diagonals, promised a "one-of-a-kind stadium" but by 1974 it was scrapped by internal bids.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The La Plata Stadium was finally completed in 2003.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] In the case of Tucuman, an ambitious stadium of 70,000 spectators had been promised in Horco Molle, similar to the current Racing Club Stadium, along with the roof.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The Tucuman venue was temporarily suspended in 1974 and was decommissioned the following year, given the intensity of the actions of the guerrillas and the Armed Forces in the province.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Three new stadiums were built (Olympic Stadium in Córdoba; World Cup Stadium in Mar del Plata; and Mendoza City Stadium in Mendoza) and the other three were remodelled.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Of the six venues used, the River Plate Stadium in Buenos Aires was the largest and most used venue, hosting nine total matches, including the final.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The Olympic Stadium in Cordoba hosted eight matches, the stadiums in Mendoza, Rosario and Mar del Plata each hosted six matches and José Amalfitani Stadium in Buenos Aires hosted three matches — bringing the Argentine capital and largest city's total to 12 — nearly a third of all the matches played.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Brazil was forced by tournament organisers to play all three of its first group matches in Mar del Plata; there had been rumours and allegations of the organisers deliberately sabotaging the Minella stadium's pitch to weaken Brazil's chances of success.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] For a list of all squads that appeared in the final tournament, see *1978 FIFA World Cup squads*.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] With six goals, Mario Kempes was the top scorer in the tournament.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] In total, 102 goals were scored by 62 players, with three of them credited as own goals.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] A group of journalists and experts selected the best player of the 1978 tournament, and their selection is recognised by the FIFA website.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] FIFA recognises only this selection besides the Golden Ball award.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Hans Krankl received the same number of votes as Dirceu at the time, and was not chosen as the third best player by FIFA later.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] In 1986, FIFA published a report that ranked all teams in each World Cup up to and including 1986, based on progress in the competition, overall results and quality of the opposition.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] A controversy surrounding the 1978 World Cup was that only two years prior to the competition the Argentine government of Isabel Perón had been replaced in a coup d'état by a military dictatorship known as the National Reorganization Process.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Between the time that the military junta took over government and the time the World Cup started, foreign journalists were concerned about how Argentine newspaper reporters and editors were being treated by the regime, in attempting to get leftist members out of the picture.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The new government targeted any parts of society that they saw were trying to undermine them.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Less than a year before the World Cup, in September 1977, Interior Minister General Albano Harguindeguy, stated that 5,618 people had recently disappeared.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The junta also practised censorship since it was established, which encouraged less reports on the real situation in Argentina.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] This was done as an attempt to change the character of the Argentine people.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] During the buildup to the tournament, the military dictatorship viewed the World Cup as a strategic opportunity to legitimise its rule and promote an image of stability amid widespread repression.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Scholars argue that the junta spent enormously on stadiums, infrastructure, and propaganda campaigns, not for economic development but to stage an international spectacle capable of masking state terror.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Government-controlled media portrayed Argentina as peaceful and orderly, while international correspondents later reported censorship, surveillance, and restrictions on movement while covering the event.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Just months before the World Cup, the Argentine regime launched a campaign to silence any disapproval of the government from the people.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] However, over the course of the tournament, the regime ceased the operation to avoid giving off their authoritarianism and receiving criticism from all over the world, but international newspapers and human rights organisations have already criticised Argentina as host for the next World Cup.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The presence of ESMA so close to the Monumental Stadium became a powerful symbol of the contradictions of the tournament.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Testimonies collected after the dictatorship describe prisoners hearing match-day cheers while torture and interrogations occurred inside the facility.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Historians note that these overlapping soundscapes underscore how national celebration and clandestine state violence coexisted during the event, shaping later memory of the World Cup as both a moment of sporting triumph and a period of profound human rights abuse.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The military forces that had control over Argentina at the time wanted to hold that power for as long as they could, but with a different perspective.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The use of repression, torture, kidnapping, and assassination was becoming an everyday reality, with 30,000 people murdered between 1976 and 1983, the end of the dictatorship.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] People wondered why FIFA would allow the World Cup to go on under these circumstances and that 15 other countries, most of which are old democracies, would participate in the tournament.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] However, it is simply because of the dominant notion that football or soccer, or any sport for that matter, belong to civil society, giving the assumption that state policies wouldn't interfere with the passion and enthusiasm of fans.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Civil society groups, most notably the Mothers of the Plaza de Mayo, used the World Cup’s global visibility to denounce the disappearance of their children.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] They held weekly marches during the tournament, attracting foreign journalists and making the dictatorship’s human rights record visible to international audiences for the first time.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Their activism challenged the junta’s effort to project unity and control during the games and became foundational to human rights mobilisation in Argentina.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] International observers widely noted that the dictatorship attempted to use the World Cup to normalise Argentina’s global image.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] According to historians, military leaders believed that a successful tournament would showcase Argentina as a modern, orderly nation while drawing attention away from the forced disappearances, torture centers, and mass repression taking place at the same time.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] This strategy mirrored efforts by earlier authoritarian regimes, such as those in Nazi Germany and Fascist Italy, which relied on major sporting events to project legitimacy and political strength.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Despite the regime’s censorship apparatus, foreign journalists in Argentina continued reporting on the growing number of *desaparecidos* and the repressive climate.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Many correspondents described a palpable military presence in the streets, with frequent ID checks, unmarked cars, and armed patrols near stadiums and transportation hubs.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] These accounts helped counter the junta’s attempt to use the World Cup as a distraction and contributed to broader international condemnation of state violence.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The government invested more than ten times the original projected budget for the tournament, a financial decision scholars consider politically motivated rather than economically rational.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The overspending contributed to rising inflation and public debt that later intensified Argentina’s economic crisis in the early 1980s.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] In this sense, the World Cup not only intersected with the dictatorship’s political agenda but also deepened the long-term financial instability that emerged as a defining feature of the regime’s final years.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Because of the political turmoil, some countries, most notably the Netherlands and Sweden, considered publicly whether they should participate in the event.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Despite this, all teams eventually took part without restrictions.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] However, most notably, Dutch star Johan Cruyff, who was considered the best player in the previous 1974 FIFA World Cup, refused to take part in the 1978 World Cup, even though he earlier participated in the 1978 FIFA World Cup qualification.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Allegations that Cruyff refused to participate because of political convictions were denied by him 30 years later—he and his family had been the victims of a kidnapping attempt a few months before the tournament.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Several criminals entered his house in Barcelona at night and tied him and his family up at gunpoint.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] One player, Ralf Edström, was arrested for speaking to someone in Buenos Aires; however, the Argentine military released him upon recognising that he was a Swedish footballer, not an ordinary person.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Amnesty International announced their strategy for Argentina in 1978.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] French activists also organised some of the largest international protests against the tournament.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] In Paris, human-rights groups and left-wing political movements formed COBA (Comité pour le Boycott de l’Argentine), which produced posters, newsletters, and public demonstrations calling attention to the dictatorship.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] By 1978, over 200 local COBA committees existed across France, illustrating the extent to which the World Cup had become a focal point for transnational activism.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Paris was a center of unanimity for the victims of the Argentine dictatorship, which launched a campaign to boycott the 1978 World Cup.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] In the city, they made posters, publications or any kind of information that expressed opposition to the World Cup under a dictatorship.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The first calls to boycott were published in the daily *Le Monde* in October 1977.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Later, a boycott committee was organised, which brought together human-rights militants and left-wing activists.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Enriqueta Maroni, member of the Mothers of Plaza de Mayo, became internationally known after being interviewed by Dutch television where she told openly about the crimes of the dictatorship.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Outside Latin America and Europe, human rights organisations in the United States, Canada, and Australia also launched independent campaigns to draw attention to the dictatorship’s crimes.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Amnesty International chapters across North America published fact sheets about forced disappearances and organised letter-writing drives to pressure FIFA and national governments to condemn Argentina’s repression.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Although these efforts did not lead to a boycott, they helped internationalise the human rights movement that grew dramatically in the late 1970s.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Sports magazines and newspapers in several countries ran dual coverage of both the athletic tournament and the political situation.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Some outlets published investigative reports on secret detention centers and testimonies from exiled Argentines.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] These stories challenged the junta’s narrative that Argentina was safe, unified, and politically stable.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The visibility of these reports demonstrated the limits of the regime’s propaganda efforts and revealed how global media attention complicated the dictatorship’s attempt to control information.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Scholars note that the political debate surrounding the 1978 World Cup marked one of the earliest moments when international sporting events were openly criticised as potential instruments of authoritarian image-making.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] This contributed to broader discussions about the ethics of hosting major competitions in non-democratic states, foreshadowing contemporary debates about “sportswashing” in global politics.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Argentina's controversial and favourable decisions in their matches have caused many to view their eventual win as illegitimate; many cite the political climate and worldwide pressure on the Argentine government as the reason for these decisions.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Desperate to prove their stability and prominence to the world after their coup two years earlier, the government used whatever means necessary to ensure that the team would progress far in the tournament.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Academic research has emphasised that while no conclusive proof of government-orchestrated match fixing exists, circumstantial evidence—including diplomatic pressure, economic negotiations, and testimonies from Peruvian officials—has sustained debate for decades.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The high political stakes for the junta, which relied on World Cup success to bolster its legitimacy, intensified suspicions surrounding Argentina’s 6–0 victory over Peru.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Suspicions of match fixing arose even before the tournament began; Lajos Baróti, the head coach of Argentina's first opponents, Hungary, said that "everything, even the air, is in favor of Argentina".
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] He also talked about the financial imperative to have Argentina win the World Cup: "The success of Argentina is financially so important to the tournament".
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] More controversy surrounded the host, Argentina, as all of their games in the first round kicked off at night, giving the Argentines the advantage of knowing where they stood in the group.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] This issue would arise again in Spain 1982, which prompted FIFA to change the rules so that the final two group games in subsequent World Cups (as well as in every other international tournament, starting with the UEFA Euro 1984) would be played simultaneously.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] In their second group stage game against France, Argentina were the beneficiaries of multiple favourable calls.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Further accusations have surrounded the game Argentina and Peru played in the second round of the tournament.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Following Brazil's 3–1 win over Poland, Argentina needed to win by a margin of four goals to proceed to the final and did so by defeating Peru by 6–0.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] There were allegations that the authoritarian Argentine military government interfered to ensure Argentina would defeat Peru through intimidation, though these were denied by Peruvian captain Héctor Chumpitaz and several Peruvian players.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Some accusations originated in the Brazilian media and pointed to the fact that the Peruvian goalkeeper, Ramón Quiroga, had been born in Argentina.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] There was also an alleged deal, reported by the British media as an anonymous rumour, that involved the delivery of a large grain shipment to Peru by Argentina and the unfreezing of a Peruvian bank account that was held by the Argentine Central Bank.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Another alleged deal, recounted by the son of a Colombian drug lord in a controversial book, involved the Peruvian team being bribed without any political implications.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] A third alleged deal, described by the Peruvian leftist ex-senator Genaro Ledesma, encompassed sending 13 Peruvian dissidents exiled in Argentina back to Peru.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Three months before the World Cup, Argentina had beaten Peru 3–1 in Lima, their head-to-head record was 15–3 in favour of the host nation, and Peru had never beaten Argentina away from home.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] However, Peru had conceded only six goals in their previous five games in the World Cup.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] During the first half, Peru hit the post twice after two counters when the game was 0–0.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Argentina managed to get 2–0 ahead before the end of the first 45 minutes.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] During the second half, Argentina was 4–0 ahead when Peru had another clear chance.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Argentina kept attacking and scored twice more, making it 6–0 and surpassing the required margin.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The match has since become one of the most studied games in World Cup history, not because of its tactical content but because of its entanglement with Cold War politics, inter-American relations, and the symbolic weight of Argentina’s authoritarian context.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] Whether or not any explicit arrangement occurred, the game remains a key example of how international football can become deeply intertwined with political strategies and national narratives.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] In addition, Maradona's usual position of number 10 (play-making attacking midfielder) was taken by Mario Kempes, who ended up as the Best Player and Top Goal Scorer.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] The debate over Maradona’s omission remains a reminder of how individual players were affected by the tournament’s political stakes.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1978-fifa-world-cup] While some argue that Menotti’s decision was strictly athletic, others point to the broader pressures and uncertainties surrounding public life under the junta as contextual factors that shaped coaching choices.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1990-fiba-world-championship] The **1990 FIBA World Championship** was the 11th FIBA World Championship, the international basketball world championship for men's national teams.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1990-fiba-world-championship] It was hosted by Argentina from 8 to 19 August 1990.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1990-fiba-world-championship] The final phase of the competition was held at the Luna Park, Buenos Aires.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1990-fiba-world-championship] Yugoslavia emerged as the tournament winner.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1990-fiba-world-championship] This was the last World Championship in which the country participated before its dissolution.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1990-fiba-world-championship] Likewise, the Soviet Union participated in its final tournament before its dissolution.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1990-fiba-world-championship] This was the first ever FIBA World Championship (now called FIBA Basketball World Cup) tournament, in which non-American current NBA players that had also already played in an official regular season NBA game could participate.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1990-fiba-world-championship] There were 16 teams taking part in the 1990 World Cup of Basketball.
[src:córdoba-argentina/1990-fiba-world-championship] The top two finishers from Groups I and II advance to the final round.
[src:córdoba-argentina/2002-fivb-men-s-volleyball-world-championship] The **2002 FIVB Men's Volleyball World Championship** was the 15th edition of the event, organised by the world's governing body, the FIVB.
[src:córdoba-argentina/2002-fivb-men-s-volleyball-world-championship] It was held in Salta, Córdoba, Mar del Plata, Buenos Aires, Santa Fé and San Juan in Argentina from September 28 to October 13, 2002.
[src:córdoba-argentina/2002-fivb-men-s-volleyball-world-championship] All times are Argentina Time (UTC−03:00).
[src:córdoba-argentina/2002-fivb-men-s-volleyball-world-championship] The official competition symbol the "Minto".
[src:córdoba-argentina/2002-fivb-men-s-volleyball-world-championship] The design is based on sport ball and volleyball.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] As of the 2020 census, Aguascalientes has a population of 1,425,607 inhabitants, most of whom live in its capital city, also named Aguascalientes.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Its name means "hot waters" and originated from the abundance of hot springs originally found in the area.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] The demonym for the state's inhabitants is *hidrocálido* or *aguascalentense*.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Aguascalientes was historically known for its former railroad and textile industry, as well as wine making, an industry that remains today.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] During the 2010s Aguascalientes became the fastest-growing state in the country for the whole decade.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Aguascalientes is also well known for its San Marcos Fair (Feria Nacional de San Marcos), the largest fair in Mexico and one of the largest in Latin America.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Pre-Columbian era arrowheads, potshards, and rock paintings in the caverns of the Sierra del Laurel and near the present village of Las Negritas testify to the presence of humans in this territory for more than 20,000 years.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Later in the colonial times, Pedro Almíndez Chirino was the first Spaniard who entered the territory, perhaps by the end of 1530 or the beginning of 1531, following the instructions given by Nuño de Guzmán.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Before the arrival of the Spaniards, the territory of what is now the State of Aguascalientes was inhabited by Chichimecas, specifically the Guachichil, who made the territory difficult to access.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] In fact, the total occupation of the lands of El Bajío was a task that would take about two centuries.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] With respect to this, Viceroy Luís de Velasco offered municipal benefits to those who established settlements to confront the Chichimeca.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] And for his part, Viceroy Gastón de Peralta decided to confront them directly, which did not end with good results.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] In order to establish their presence in the vicinity, the conquistadors built several forts or presidios.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] This was a system devised by Martín Enríquez de Almanza following the strategy that had been developing in Spain throughout the Reconquista period.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] The latter was located on what are now Moctezuma and Victoria Streets, although some historians place it on the Calle 5 de Mayo (once the Camino Real) at Moctezuma, just in front of the Plaza de Armas.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] This was a fortress whose purpose was the protection of the Valle de los Romero and the road to Zacatecas, entering this way to secure the passage of convoys loaded with silver and other metals.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Gerónimo de Orozco, following that order, looked for someone who would accept the king's order and found a man named Juan de Montoro in the city of Santa María de los Lagos.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] He accepted the assignment and, accompanied by eleven other people, headed to the territory and thus founded the town of Aguas Calientes on October 22, 1575.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] It has been noted that it was called San Marcos originally, changing its name on August 18, 1611, to the Villa of Our Lady of the Assumption of Aguas Calientes.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] And finally, from June 2, 1875, it was called the Villa of Our Lady of the Assumption of Aguas Calientes; later changing to the city of Aguascalientes, which remains its name today.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] In the act of its establishment, the Villa de San Marcos (Aguascalientes) was awarded the highest mayoral jurisdiction under the Kingdom of New Galicia.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] As of December 4, 1786, on the occasion of the issuance of the "Ordinance of Mayors", it became a quartermaster sub-delegation.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] On April 24, 1789, by order of the Superior Board of Royal Property, the sub-delegation of Aguascalientes became a dependency of Zacatecas.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] In the Mexican War of Independence, men such as Valentin Gómez Farías, Rafael Iriarte, Rafael Vázquez, and Pedro Parga led some of the first revolutionary activities in the territory which is today the state of Aguascalientes.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Confusion has arisen regarding the exact date when Aguascalientes formally separated from the territory of Zacatecas.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] By virtue of having, de facto, defeated the liberal government of Zacatecas by rising against the central government, president Antonio López de Santa Anna passed through Aguascalientes, where he was well received by the people who had wanted to separate from Zacatecas for some time.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] The second requirement not being completed, the constitutional congress convened again to develop the centralized constitution that would be known later as the Seven Laws.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] The constitution did not acknowledge Aguascalientes in the rank of department, but it saw fit to eliminate the states, together with the federal regime, replacing the states with departments, and because of this it continued to belong to Zacatecas.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] What can be said, since in the local constitution of Zacatecas of 1825, Aguascalientes was contemplated as a member of said state.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] It was general José Mariano Salas who, on August 5, 1846, announced the reestablishment of federalism, convening a constitutional congress that declared current the constitution of 1824, but still didn't consider Aguascalientes as a state.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Subsequently, on May 18, 1847, amendments were approved to the Constitution of 1824, but neither granted to Aguascalientes the status of a state.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] That brought about a war between Aguascalientes and Zacatecas, and as a consequence Zacatecas would strengthen the partitions, now municipalities, of Cavillo and Rincón de Romos.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] In July 1848, Aguascalientes accepted the peaceful annexation to Zacatecas; but continued making efforts to separate through Miguel García Rojas.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] It was not until December 10, 1853, that López de Santa Anna, using his extraordinary powers, issued a decree declaring Aguascalientes a department, based on the decrees of December 30, 1836, and June 30, 1838, without ever referring to the one from March 23, 1835.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Finally, in the project that would be the Constitution of 1857, that was presented on June 16, 1856, Aguascalientes was included as a state in Article 43; it was passed unanimously by the 79 deputies present, ensuring the establishment of the state of Aguascalientes on December 10, 1856.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] On September 16, 1857, on the strength of said constitution, Lic.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Jesús Terán Peredo reclaimed his post as constitutional governor of the state.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] In the independent state, men such as Jesús R.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Macías, Manuel Rangel, Augustín Orona, José María Arellano and many others distinguished themselves in the War of Reform.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Silvestre Dorador, Román Morales, Pedro Vital, Alfonso Guerrero Aguilera and Alberto Fuentes Dávila were forerunners of the Revolution.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] The explosion of the Maderist movement embraced the cause in the company of some other compatriots, and the rebel action of the town and the region stayed formalized.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] The state is located about 480 km (300 mi) from Mexico City in the macroregion of El Bajío, specifically the Bajío Occidental (western Bajío).
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] It covers 5,471 km2 (2,112 sq mi), or 0.3% of the area of the country, and has a little more than one million inhabitants.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Most of its inhabitants live in the densely populated metropolitan area of its capital city.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] It bears the name Aguascalientes taken from its largest city and capital also called Aguascalientes.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] The state mostly has a semi-arid climate, with an exception in the northwestern part of the state with the Sierra Fría mountain range having a temperate highland climate.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] It also brings large amounts of rain that eventually flows into one of the states reservoir.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Mean annual temperature of the state is around 17 to 18 °C (62.6 to 64.4 °F) in which May and June are the hottest months with mean temperatures between 22 and 23 °C (71.6 and 73.4 °F).
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] In these months, temperatures can exceed 30 °C (86.0 °F).
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] January is the coldest month, averaging 13 to 14 °C (55.4 to 57.2 °F) with temperatures dropping down to 4 °C (39.2 °F).
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Frosts frequently occur from November to February.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Mean rainfall is low, averaging 526 mm (20.7 in) and is mostly concentrated in summer with winters being dry.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] This state originated around the times of colonial Spanish influence.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] It is located in the middle of the country and is now beginning to make a name for itself as an industrial power within Mexico.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] The state was once a major silver miner and a major source of railroad transportation, the latter due to its strategic location, midway between the three most populous areas, namely Mexico City, Guadalajara, and Monterrey.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Today, Mexico's fast growing car industry is especially important in this state.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] There are two Nissan factories in Aguascalientes which together produce more than half a million cars per year.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Infiniti may build a plant to make vehicles like the QX30.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] In the rural area, Aguascalientes was once the largest national producer of grapes and wines.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] This tradition ceased gradually due to the Spanish Royalty's wishes that grape and wine production be limited to the mother country.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Thanks to the influx of immigrants into Mexico, the wineries and vineyards remain and flourish.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Guavas are also produced in the state, specifically in the municipality of Calvillo.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] This county is one of the richest counties in Aguascalientes.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] However, recently it has also benefited from heavier tourism, since the capital city has gained prestige and status as a national destination for its colonial beauty and cleanliness.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] In addition, the haciendas and baths around the state have historic and recreational importance.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Although this state is not often billed as a tourist center, international visitors, as well as citizens from all over Mexico, are attracted to San Marcos Fair, which is considered the national fair of Mexico and contributes much to Mexico's economy.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Recently, its capital city has gained the reputation as a great destination for its superb colonial architecture visible in the colonial center, as well as the modernity and dynamism in the outskirts.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Jesús Terán Peredo International Airport, where 9 flights per day depart to Mexico City, Tijuana, Dallas/Fort Worth and Houston.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] The city also hosts many conventions every year.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] It benefits from its excellent central location.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] The city is also famed for its environment of relaxation, and for its safety and cleanliness, as it is often described by people when traveling to this part of the country for conventions or tourism.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] A few tourists explore the former mining towns in the north of the state (in the municipalities of Asientos and Tepezalá), which are now almost ghost cities.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] The haciendas, hot springs, and baths scattered around the state are also of historical and recreational relevance.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] The municipality of Calvillo has a humid subtropical climate, The largest producer of guavas in Mexico, it attracts some fans of watersports to its reservoirs.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] The state has a Natural Protected Reserve in the higher mountains called Sierra Fría.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Located at a height of 2,500 to 3,000 m (8,202 to 9,843 ft) above sea level, it comprises oak and pine forests.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Its attractions include observing exuberant landscape and wide ravines, in which, there are pumas, lynxes, boar, white-tailed deer, wild turkey, raccoons and many other animals.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] There are steep-sided cycle paths, camping and picnic areas as well as several hunting clubs.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] It is the mountain climate and fauna that attracts locals for camping activities.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] In winter, the temperature sometimes falls to −4.44 °C (24.01 °F) when the weather is poor.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Usually, Sierra Fría is the only part of the state that gets snow during winter.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] The city of Aguascalientes is called "el corazón" which means "the heart" of Mexico because it lies in the middle of the country.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] This city is often considered, by its locals, to be one of the safest and cleanest in Mexico.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Also, the city of Aguascalientes is known as "the land of the good people".
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] The state has one football team in the Mexican Premiere League, Club Necaxa; one professional baseball team in the Mexican League, Rieleros de Aguascalientes; and one professional basketball team, the Panteras de Aguascalientes.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Aguascalientes also has important racetracks for car and motorbike races at a national and international level.
[src:córdoba-argentina/aguascalientes] Newspapers of Aguascalientes include: *Ahí*, *El Heraldo de Aguascalientes*, *El Sol del Centro de Aguascalientes*, *Hidrocálido*, *LJA*, and *Picacho Panorama de Aguascalientes*.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] He began his systems engineering career at the Instituto Universitario Aeronáutico.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] While studying there, he published his first work, *Los mitos setentistas: Mentiras fundamentales sobre la década del 70*.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] This book allowed him to obtain a scholarship to study counterterrorism at the William J.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] Perry Center for Hemispheric Defense Studies at the National Defense University, in Washington, D.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] C., an institution of the United States Department of Defense.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] When he returned to Argentina in 2011, he abandoned his engineering career.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] He holds a Licentiate Degree on Politics Sciences from the National University of Córdoba, and a master's degree in Philosophy from University of Navarra, Spain.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] In 2013, Laje published *Cuando el relato es una farsa: la respuesta al relato kirchnerista* with the writer Nicolás Márquez, where he criticizes Kirchnerism's position on the 1976–1983 dictatorship in Argentina.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] The book was rejected by local human rights organizations and organizations supporting trials for crimes against humanity, which repudiated it and managed to cancel its presentation in Bahía Blanca.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] In 2016, also together with Márquez, they published *El libro negro de la nueva izquierda: Ideología de género o subversión cultural*.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] In it, they criticize third-wave feminism, and what they call "gender ideology", which are elements they consider to be tools of Cultural Marxism.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] This book generated a controversy in stating that a feminist supposedly supported the pedophile activist movement.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] Subsequently, the actress and host Malena Pichot interviewed Laje on a radio program, generating a debate which later went viral on social networks.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] Laje also participated in a debate with the presenter Patricia del Río, on the Peruvian radio station RPP.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] In 2018, the book was presented at the 44th edition of the Buenos Aires Book Fair, where it provoked rejection from human rights organizations, social and political organizations.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] They responded with "songs and slogans referring to denialism, hatred, and discrimination that these authors promote".
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] Laje calls himself a paleolibertarian, minarchist, and anti-feminist.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] He is a strong opponent of abortion, making him a pro-life activist.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] His ideas have been considered ultra-conservative and far-right by different media outlets.
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] On numerous occasions, Laje has been called sexist, transphobic, and homophobic, but according to him, "he hates no one".
[src:córdoba-argentina/agustín-laje] Laje defines gender ideology as a set of anti-scientific ideas that, for authoritarian political purposes, uproots its nature from human sexuality, and tends to explain it exclusively from culture.
[src:córdoba-argentina/alicia-ghiragossian] Alicia Ghiragossian was born in 1936, the daughter of Armenian parents in Córdoba, Argentina.
[src:córdoba-argentina/alicia-ghiragossian] Her parents had emigrated to Argentina after the Armenian genocide in the Ottoman Empire.
[src:córdoba-argentina/alicia-ghiragossian] She obtained a law degree form the University of Buenos Aires and began practicing as a lawyer, but abandoned the profession to pursue a publishing career.
[src:córdoba-argentina/alicia-ghiragossian] She moved to Los Angeles in 1971 where she resided until her death in 2014.
[src:córdoba-argentina/alicia-ghiragossian] In 1967, Ghiragossian published a collection of poetry (*Being and Punctuation*), having published her first book the previous year.
[src:córdoba-argentina/alicia-ghiragossian] The collection was translated into Italian and illustrated by the Spanish artist Pablo Picasso.
[src:córdoba-argentina/alicia-ghiragossian] The same year, an edition of her poems (*Roots and Essence*) was translated into Armenian, and became a bestseller in Armenia and among the Armenian diaspora.
[src:córdoba-argentina/alicia-ghiragossian] Writing in Spanish, English, and Armenian, she went on to publish more than 60 books, most of which are poetry collections.
[src:córdoba-argentina/alicia-ghiragossian] She also translated an edition of the Armenian poet Raffi into Spanish.
[src:córdoba-argentina/alicia-ghiragossian] Ghiragossian has been variously recognised for her poetry.
[src:córdoba-argentina/alicia-ghiragossian] She was nominated for the 1997 Nobel Prize in Literature; the award was later given to the Italian playwright Dario Fo.
[src:córdoba-argentina/alicia-ghiragossian] In the same year, she was made an honorary citizen of Armenia, while the Armenian National Academy of Sciences awarded her an honorary doctorate.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba was founded as a settlement on 6 July 1573 by Spanish conquistador Jerónimo Luis de Cabrera, who named it after the Spanish city of Córdoba.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] It was one of the early Spanish colonial capitals of the region of present-day Argentina (the oldest Argentine city is Santiago del Estero, founded in 1553).
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The National University of Córdoba, the oldest university of the country, was founded in 1613 by the Jesuit Order, and Córdoba has earned the nickname *La Docta* ("the learned").
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The campus belongs today to the historical museum of the National University of Córdoba, which has been the second-largest university in the country since the early years of the 20th century (after the University of Buenos Aires), in number of students, faculty, and academic programs.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba is also known for its historical movements, such as the Cordobazo of May 1969 and *La Reforma del '18* (known as the University Revolution in English) of 1918.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In 1570 the Viceroy of Peru, Francisco de Toledo, entrusted the Spanish settler Jerónimo Luis de Cabrera with the task of founding and populating a settlement in the Punilla Valley.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Cabrera sent an expedition of 48 men to the territory of the Comechingones.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] He divided the principal column that entered through the north of the provincial territory at Villa María.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The expedition of one hundred men set foot on what today is Córdoba on 24 June 1573.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Cabrera called the nearby river San Juan (today Suquía).
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The settlement was officially founded on 6 July of the same year and named *Córdoba de la Nueva Andalucía*, possibly in honour of ancestors of the founder's wife, who originally came from Córdoba, Spain.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The foundation of the city took place on the left bank of the river on the advice of Francisco de Torres.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The area was inhabited by aboriginal people called Comechingones, who lived in communities called *ayllus*.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] After four years, having repelled attacks by the aborigines, the settlement's authorities moved it to the opposite bank of the Suquía River in 1577.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Lieutenant Governor at the time, Don Lorenzo Suárez de Figueroa, planned the first layout of the city as a grid of 70 blocks.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Once the city core had been moved to its current location, the population stabilized.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The city's economy blossomed due to trade with the cities in the north.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In 1599, the religious order of the Jesuits arrived in the settlement.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] They established a Novitiate in 1608 and, in 1610, the Colegio Maximo, which became the University of Córdoba in 1613 (today National University of Córdoba), the fourth-oldest in the Americas.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The local Jesuit church remains one of the oldest buildings in South America and contains the Monserrat Secondary School, a church, and residential buildings.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] To maintain such a project, the Jesuits operated five *Reducciones* in the surrounding fertile valleys, including Caroya, Jesús María, Santa Catalina, Alta Gracia and Candelaria.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The farm and the complex (started in 1615, had to be vacated by the Jesuits following the 1767 decree by King Charles III of Spain that expelled the Jesuit order from the continent.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Franciscans then operated the Jesuits' foundations until 1853, when the Jesuits returned to the Americas.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Nevertheless, the university and the high-school were nationalized a year later.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Each estancia has its own church and set of buildings, around which towns grew, such as Alta Gracia, the closest to the Block.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In 1776, King Carlos III created the Viceroyalty of the Río de la Plata, in which Córdoba stays in 1785 as the Government Intendency of Córdoba, including the current territories of the provinces of Córdoba, La Rioja and the region of Cuyo.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] According to the 1760 census, the population of the city was 22,000 inhabitants.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] During the May Revolution in 1810, the widespread opinion of the most notable citizens was of continuing respecting the orders of Fernando VII, attitude assumed by the local authorities, which led to the Liniers Counter-revolution.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] This position was not shared by the Dean Gregorio Funes, who was adhering to the revolutionary ideas, beside supporting contact with Manuel Belgrano and Juan José Castelli.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In March 1816, the Argentine Congress met in Tucumán for an independence resolution.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba sent Eduardo Pérez Bulnes, Jerónimo Salguero de Cabrera, José Antonio Cabrera, and to the Canon of the cathedral Michael Calixto of the Circle, all of them of autonomous position.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The 1820s belonged to caudillos, since the country was in full process of formation.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Until 1820 a central government taken root in Buenos Aires existed, but the remaining thirteen provinces felt that after 9 July 1816 what had happened it was simply a change of commander.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Battle of Cepeda pitted the commanders of the Littoral against the inland forces.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Finally, the Federales obtained the victory, for what the country remained since then integrated by 13 autonomous provinces, on the national government having been dissolved.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] From this way the period known like about the Provincial Autonomies began.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] From this moment the provinces tried to create a federal system that was integrating them without coming to good port, this mainly for the regional differences of every province.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Two Córdoba figures stood out in this period: Governor Juan Bautista Bustos, who was an official of the Army of the North and in 1820 was supervised by the troops quartered in Arequito, a town near Córdoba, and his ally and later enemy, General José María Paz.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In 1821, Bustos repelled the invasion of Córdoba on the part of Francisco Ramírez and his Chilean ally, General José Miguel Carrera.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The conflict originated in a dispute with the power system that included the provinces of Buenos Aires, Córdoba and Santa Fe; according to the 1822 census the total population of Córdoba was of 11,552 inhabitants.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] At the end of the 19th century the process of national industrialization began with the height of the economic agro-exporting model, principally of meats and cereals.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] This process is associated with the European immigration who began to settle the city, generally possessing the education and enterprising capacity appropriate for the development of industry.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] At the beginning of the 20th century the city had 90,000 inhabitants.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The city's physiognomy changed considerably following the construction of new avenues, walks and public squares, as well as the installation of an electrified tram system, in 1909.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In 1918, Córdoba was the epicentre of a movement known as the University Reform, which then spread to the rest of the Universities of the country, Americas and Spain.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The development of the domestic market, the British investments that facilitated European settlement, the development of the railways on the pampas rapidly industrialized the city.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba's industrial sector first developed from the need to transform raw materials such as leather, meats and wool for export.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In 1927, the Military Aircraft Manufacturer (FMA) was inaugurated.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The facility would become one of the most important in the world after World War II with the arrival of German technical personnel.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] From 1952, its production began to diversify, to constitute the base of the former Institute Aerotécnico, the state-owned company Aeronautical and Mechanical Industries of the State (IAME).
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba was chosen as the site of The *Instituto Aerotécnico* that later became the *Fábrica Militar de Aviones*.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] It employed the Focke Wulf men until President Juan Perón was ousted by a coup in 1955.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba, according to the census of 1947, had almost 400,000 inhabitants (a quarter of the province's total).
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Subsequent industrial development led thousands of rural families to the city, doubling its population and turning Córdoba into the second largest city in Argentina, after Buenos Aires, by 1970.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The city's population and economic growth moderated, afterwards, though living standards rose with the increase in the national consumption of Córdoba's industrial products, as well as the development of other sectors of economic activity.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba's current economic diversity is due to a vigorous services sector and the demand for agro-industrial and railway equipment and, in particular, the introduction of U.S. and European automakers after 1954.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] 1295 29 December 1893, the limits of the city of Córdoba are delineated in the northern part, South, East and West located to 12 km (7 mi) from San Martín Square which means that the common land has 24 km (15 mi) from side.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The city, adjoins in the northern territory with Colón Department summarizing a total surface of 562.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The city is located in the plain of the Humid Pampa, to the east of the oriental cord of Córdoba Hills or Sierras Chicas, also known as the Sierras Cordobesas, which has an average height of 550 m.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] It spreads at the foot of the mount, on both banks of the River Suquía, and flows into the San Roque reservoir; from there, the Primero River goes east into the plains surrounding the city of Córdoba.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Once inside the city, the *La Cañada* stream meets the Rio Primero near the city centre area.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Two kilometers to the east, *Isla de los Patos* (Ducks Island) was repopulated with ducks and swans in the 1980s.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] It was reported in March 2006 that a large number of ducks had died due to unspecified causes.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Pollution caused by chemical waste is suspected as the cause, but avian influenza is also being investigated.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Beyond the city limits, the river flows towards the Algarrobos swamp and ends its course on the southern coast of the Mar Chiquita (or Mar de Ansenuza) salt lake.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] All in all, the river has a length of approximately 200 km (124 mi) and carries, on average, 9.7 m³/s, with minimum of 2 m³/s and maximum of 24 m³/s with a peak during the summer months.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Pollution of the water and of the riverbank is a major environmental issue in Córdoba.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Periodic cleaning operations are carried out to increase the quality of the water and to preserve the viability of fishing, both in the San Roque reservoir area and downstream.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The climate of the city of Córdoba, and that of most of the province, is humid subtropical (*Cwa*, according to the Köppen climate classification), moderated by the Pampas winds, cold winds that blow from the South-western quadrant, which originate in Antarctica.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Summers run from late November till early March, and bring days between 28 °C (82 °F) and 33 °C (91 °F) and night between 15 °C (59 °F) and 19 °C (66 °F) with frequent thunderstorms.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] By late February or early March, nights start getting cooler and, in March, highs average 27 °C (81 °F) and lows 15 °C (59 °F); after cold fronts, lows below 10 °C (50 °F) and highs below 20 °C (68 °F) are recorded in this month.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] April is significantly drier already; highs reach 24 °C (75 °F) on average and lows 12 °C (54 °F), creating very pleasant conditions.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In some years, temperatures can approach or even reach the freezing point in late April; however, heat waves of up to 33 °C (91 °F) are still possible, but nights are rarely as hot as in the summer.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] May usually brings the first frosts, and very dry weather, with under 20 mm (1 in) of rain expected.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Highs average 21 °C (70 °F) and lows average 8 °C (46 °F); however, when cold waves reach the area, highs may stay below 8 °C (46 °F) and lows can be well below freezing.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Winter lasts from late May till early September, and bring average highs of 18 °C (64 °F) and lows of 4 °C (39 °F).
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] However, strong northwesterly winds downsloping from the mountains can bring what is known as "Veranito" (little summer) with highs of up to 30 °C (86 °F) or more and dusty, windy weather (but dry, pleasant nights) for 2–3 days.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Snowfall is very rare in the city, but more frequent in the outskirts where the Sierras begin ; sleet may fall every once in a while.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The record low temperature for Córdoba is −8.3 °C (17.1 °F).
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In June, only 3.5 mm (0.1 in) of rain are expected, compared to 168 mm (6.6 in) in January.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Spring is extremely variable and windy: there may be long stretches of cool, dry weather and cold nights followed by intense heat waves up to 38 °C (100 °F), followed by the most severe thunderstorms with hail and high winds.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] It is not unusual to see temperatures drop 20 °C (36 °F) from one day to another, or to have frost following extreme heat.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Drought is most common in this season, when the normal summer rainfall arrives later than expected.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] By October, days are warm at 26 °C (79 °F) but nights remain cold at 11 °C (52 °F), by late November, the weather resembles summer weather with cooler nights.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The wealthier suburbs west of the city are located at slightly higher altitudes, which allows cool breezes to blow in the summer, bringing drier, comfortable nights during hotter periods, and more regular frost in the winter.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Generally speaking, Córdoba's daytime temperatures are very slightly warmer than Buenos Aires' but nighttime lows are usually cooler, especially in the winter.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] This, combined with a lower humidity and the possibility of fleeing to higher altitudes minutes away from the city centre, makes the climate a bit more comfortable than in the capital.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The variations or thermal extents are greater than in Buenos Aires, and lower in annual rainfall: 750 mm (30 in) / year.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The annual average temperature calculated during the 20th century was 18 °C.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In January, the hottest month of the austral summer, the average maximum is 31 °C and the minimum 17 °C.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In July, the coldest month of the year, the average temperatures are between 19 °C and 3 °C.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In winter it is very frequent that temperatures rise above 30 °C, due to the influence of the wind Zonda.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Due to the extension of the metropolitan area, there exists a difference of 5 °C between the central area and the Greater Córdoba.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The central district, a dense high-rise area is located in a depression, and it is the core of an important heat island.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In addition the city presents a phenomenon of smog, but not so dense as to present health concerns.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The largest ethnic groups in Córdoba are Italians/Italian Argentine and Spaniards/Spanish Argentine (mostly Galicians and Basques/Basque Argentine).
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Waves of immigrants from other European countries arrived in the late 19th and early 20th centuries.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] From the rest of Western Europe came immigrants from Switzerland, Germany, United Kingdom, Ireland and Scandinavia (especially Sweden).
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Other Europeans also arrived from nations such as Croatia, Poland, Hungary, Russia, Romania, Ukraine, Armenia and the Balkans (especially Greece, Serbia and Montenegro).
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] By the 1910s, 43 percent of the city population was non-native Argentine after immigration rates peaked.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Important Lebanese, Syrian and Armenian communities have had a significant presence in commerce and civic life since the beginning of the 20th century.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Most immigrants, regardless of origin, settled in the city or around Greater Córdoba.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] However, in the early stages of immigration, some formed settlements (especially agricultural settlements) in different parts of the city, often encouraged by the Argentine government and/or sponsored by private individuals and organizations.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba is the second largest city in the country in population and concentrates 40.9% of the Córdoba Province population of 3,216,993 inhabitants and represents almost 3.3% of the Argentine population, which is 43 million inhabitants.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Driven by migration both domestic and from abroad, the city's rate of population growth was an elevated 3.2% annually from 1914 to 1960; but, it has been declining steadily since then, and has averaged around 0.4% a year, since the national census of 2001.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] According to the last provincial census of 2008, the city has 1,315,540 inhabitants, representing an increase of 3.78% with regard to the 1,267,521 registered during the national census of 2001.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Greater Córdoba is the metropolitan area of the city of Córdoba, a union of medium localities of the department Colón, from the north to the south.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Greater Córdoba is the second-largest urban agglomeration in Argentina in both population and surface area.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The growth of the metropolitan area was not equal in all directions, it spreads approximately up to 50 km (31 mi) to the northwest of the Córdoba city centre in a thin succession of small localities.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] This is almost the maximum distance from the Buenos Aires city center to the most distant of its metropolitan area points; whereas in the rest of the cardinal points it comes to 15 km (9 mi).
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The city receives a constant flow of students from the northeastern and southwestern regions of Argentina and of other South American countries, owed principally to the National University of Córdoba, which increases gradually the city population.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba grows constantly, expanding especially towards the southern areas of Alta Gracia and Villa Carlos Paz.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Green spaces include different types of spaces, from small squares, up to urban, green linear parks of different scales as the river Suquia, bicycle pathways and highways.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The surface area of green spaces supported by the Municipality of Córdoba adds up to approximately 1645 hectares.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The historical centre is shaped by quadrangular blocks of some hundred thirty meters of side.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The disposition of the neighborhoods and principal avenues is radial.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] From the city centre district large avenues lead out to the most peripheral neighborhoods.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In conformity with demographic growth, the city has expanded principally to the northwest and to the southeast, following the trace of the National Route 9.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The governor, Juan Schiaretti, finalized the Circunvalaciónon on 6 July 2019, with completing the building of the last 2,8 km of the route from La Cañanada to Fuerza Aerea.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] This ended the construction of the 47 km long ring road motorway, which takes almost 34 minutes to complete.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba is home to one of the most important financial districts in South America.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The district is home to the Bank of Córdoba and other private banking institutions.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Sightseeing places include San Martín Square, the Jesuit Block (declared UNESCO World Heritage Site) and the Genaro Pérez Museum.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The streets mostly follow a regular checkerboard pattern, and the main thoroughfares are Vélez Sarsfield, Colón, General Paz, Dean Funes Avenue, and 27 April Street.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The point of origin of the city is San Martin Square, surrounded by the Municipality and Central Post Office.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Downtown Córdoba is home to large shopping malls, notably Patio Olmos.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] This mall is the result of a massive regeneration effort, recycling and refurbishing the west side old warehouses into elegant offices and commercial centres.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] An important cultural point of interest is the Palacio Ferreyra, a mansion built in 1916 based on plans by the French architect, Ernest Sanson.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Ferreyra palace was converted into the Evita Perón Museum of Fine Arts (the city's second) in 2007.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Located at the corner of Hipólito Yrigoyen and Chacabuco Avenues, it has now been restored and adapted to house the city's principal art gallery.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] New Córdoba has a number of important avenues such as *Yrigoyen* and *Vélez Sarsfield*.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Most of the university students in this growing city live in this neighbourhood, and a recent construction boom has been transforming this upscale area into the fastest-growing section in the city.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Ciudad Universitaria is a district located in the southern area of the city, next to the 17 hectares (42 acres) Sarmiento Park, the city's most important one.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Universidad Nacional de Córdoba (UNC) has most of its facilities in this area.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The UNC was the first university built in Argentina, founded by Jesuits around 1622.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Universidad Nacional de Córdoba is also famous for the "Reforma Universitaria", a student-led protest that started in March 1918 in the Medical School, in which the students rebelled against the prevailing university system.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] This was an old anachronistic system in which professors were authoritarian and inefficient, with a religiously-oriented curriculum.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Eventually this revolt led to a more secular curriculum and some significant re-structuring of the university government.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The distinctive nature of the movement derived not only from its radical demands, but also from its extremist tactics, the level of sophistication of its organization, and its major continental impact.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In fact, the Reform Movement rapidly spread from Córdoba to Lima (1919), Cuzco (1920), Santiago de Chile (1920), and Mexico (1921).
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Another important university, the UTN, dedicated to the teaching of engineering sciences, is located in this part of the city.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] There is also a gym and football stadium and tennis courts for the students.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The *Córdoba Zoo* is located in this district.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Located about 6 km (4 mi) from downtown Córdoba is the Cerro de Las Rosas.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] This very affluent neighborhood is famous for its schools, shops and educational institutions.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] This neighborhood's economic activity centers around Rafael Núñez Avenue, a long wide road that stretches for a few kilometers and has restaurants, boutiques, banks and other shops.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Over the last decade, this neighborhood has experienced steady growth; however, some of its most affluent inhabitants have moved to gated communities for security reasons.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Some of these communities, such as "Las Delicias" and "Lomas de los Carolinos", are in the old Camino a La Calera.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Córdoba public transport system includes trains, buses, trolleybuses and taxis.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Long-distance buses reach most cities and towns throughout the country.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The city is served by the nation's third-largest airport, Ingeniero Ambrosio L.V.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Taravella International Airport, a vibrant airport with domestic flights within Argentina as well as to Brazil, Chile, the Dominican Republic, Panama, Paraguay, Peru and Spain on 15 passenger airlines.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Buses are, by far, the most popular way of transportation around Córdoba Province.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] There are many different companies that provide long distance, short distance and urban services.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] They all have their own prices, that are not cheap compared to the rest of Argentina.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba is one of the Provinces with higher transportation rates.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Rail transport in Córdoba has commuter and long-distance services, all operated by the state-owned Trenes Argentinos.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] From the Mitre railway station trains depart for Villa María while the Tren de las Sierras connects the district of Alta Córdoba with Cosquín.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] From Retiro station in Buenos Aires, trains reach Córdoba twice a week with an estimated journey time of 18 hours.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Many people choose the train because of the low cost, but it takes almost twice the time that would take to do the same trip by bus (around eight hours).
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Tren de las Sierras is a tourist service that crosses part of the Valle de Punilla, Quebrada del Río Suquía and borders the Dique San Roque's Lake.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] It has two services per day with an additional service on weekends.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] It takes between 2 and 3 hours to go from Alta Córdoba Station to Cosquín.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba has two railway stations, the Córdoba (Mitre) originally built by the Central Argentine R. in 1886.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] That station has been an intermediate stop for trains to Tucumán, successively operated by Ferrocarriles Argentinos and then by private consortiums such as Ferrocentral.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The other station is Alta Córdoba, built and operated by British-owned Córdoba North Western in 1891, and currently the terminus of Tren de las Sierras.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Argentine government had planned to build a high-speed train between Buenos Aires-Rosario-Córdoba.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] It would eventually join Córdoba and Buenos Aires, with an intermediate stop in Rosario, in about 3 hours at speeds of up to 350 km/h (220 mph).
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Originally scheduled to be started in 2008, with its inauguration in 2010, the project was finally cancelled in December 2012.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The total cost of the rail had been estimated at US$4,000,000,000.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] French company Alstom, which had won the tender to build the high-speed rail, admitted paying bribes to the Argentine authorities.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] On 10 December 2007 it was announced that a consortium of Iecsa/Gela companies was to build a US$1.1 billion metro system in Córdoba.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In April 2008, President Cristina Fernández de Kirchner, signed the project into law.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The project has been suspended since 2012.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The average amount of time people spend commuting with public transit in Córdoba, for example to and from work, on a weekday is 64 min.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] 13.8% of public transit riders ride for more than two hours every day.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The average amount of time people wait at a stop or station for public transit is 21 min, while 43% of riders wait for over 20 minutes on average every day.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The average distance people usually ride on a single trip with public transit is 5 km, while 4% travel for over 12 km in a single direction.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Since World War II, Córdoba has been developing a versatile industrial base.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The biggest sectors is car and car parts manufacturing: Renault has a factory which produces a range of cars and Volkswagen has a factory specialized in the production of gearboxes.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The capital goods company CNH Industrial has also a factory in the city.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The legal service Novadios was founded in 2008 in this city.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Many suppliers (both local and foreign) manufacture car parts for these operations.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Additionally, in 2017–2018, Nissan and Mercedes-Benz began the production of their new pickup truck at the local Renault factory.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Railway construction (Materfer) and aircraft construction (Fábrica Militar de Aviones) were once significant employers, but their activities have greatly diminished.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Furthermore, there are some textile, heavy and chemical industries (e.g.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Areas around Córdoba produce vast amounts of agricultural products, and some of these are processed around the city.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Additionally, the province is one of the main producers of agricultural machinery in the country, although most of these operations are not in the city itself.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Candy company Arcor is headquartered in the city.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba has been considered the technological centre of Argentina.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Argentine *spaceport* (Centro Espacial Teófilo Tabanera), where satellites are being developed and operated for CONAE, is located in the suburb of Falda del Carmen.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The software and electronic industries are advancing and becoming significant exporters; among the leading local employers in the sector are Motorola, Vates, Intel, Electronic Data Systems, and Santex América.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The city also has a service-based economy focused on retail, professional services and financial services, where the main local player is credit card provider Tarjeta Naranja.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] It has recently emerged as a start-up hub with a growing number of angel investors, in part due to the availability of people with technology-oriented skills.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Association football is the most popular sport in Córdoba as well as in Argentina.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Several leagues and divisions compete in the local championship annually.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The city currently has three representatives in the Argentine First Division, Talleres, Belgrano, and Instituto, and also one in the second, Racing de Córdoba.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Estadio Mario Alberto Kempes hosted 8 matches in the 1978 FIFA World Cup.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Basketball is the second-most popular sport in Córdoba.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Asociación Deportiva Atenas is the most popular club, and one of the most successful in Argentina, having won the National League (LNB) seven times, and being three times winner of the South American League.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba was one of the host cities of the official Basketball World Cup for its 1967 and 1990 editions.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Cordoba was also a host for the 2002 FIVB Men's Volleyball World Championship and organized the UCI BMX World Championships in 2000.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Rugby union is also a very popular sport in Córdoba, which has close to 20 teams with many divisions.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Tala Rugby Club, Club La Tablada, Córdoba Athletic Club (one of the oldest clubs in Argentina and founded by the British who worked in the building of the Argentine Railroads around 1882), Jockey Club Córdoba, and Club Universitario de Córdoba are some of the most prestigious teams.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba is one of the strongest rugby places in Argentina, and is the home of many international players.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Many of the great players in Argentina and Italy began their careers in the Córdoba's rugby clubs.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In tennis, since 2019, the Córdoba Open is also held at the "Polo Deportivo Kempes", a sports complex next to Estadio Mario Alberto Kempes.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Golf and tennis are also very popular; notable players who started playing in Córdoba include Ángel "Pato" Cabrera and Eduardo "Gato" Romero (b.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] 1954) in golf and David Nalbandian in tennis.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Argentine stage of the World Rally Championship has been run near Córdoba since 1984.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Motorsport events also take place at Autódromo Oscar Cabalén, such as TC2000 but has hosted Stock Car Brasil and Formula Truck.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Córdoba has long been one of Argentina's main educational centers, with 6 universities and several postsecondary colleges.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Students from the entire country, as well as neighbouring countries attend the local universities, giving the city a distinct atmosphere.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The National University of Córdoba, established since 1613, is the 4th oldest in the Americas and the first in Argentina.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] It has about 105,000 students, and offers degrees in a wide variety of subjects in the sciences, applied sciences, social sciences, humanities and arts.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Catholic University of Córdoba is the oldest private university in Córdoba, it has nearly 10,000 students.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Aeronautic University Institute, run by the Argentine Air Force, offers degrees in aeronautical, telecommunications and electronic engineering, as well as information systems, accounting, logistics and administration.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Instituto Tecnológico Córdoba was created jointly by the six universities located in the city to support technological development in the region.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Furthermore, the Universidad Siglo 21 and Universidad Blas Pascal are private universities in the city.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Air Force Academy and the Air Force NCOs School are both located in the city outskirts.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] There is an Italian international school, Escuela Dante Alighieri.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The area once had a German school, Deutsche Schule Cordoba.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Museums include the Caraffa Fine Arts Museum, founded in 1916, and the Evita Fine Arts Museum, founded in 2007.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Paseo del Buen Pastor cultural center opened in 2007.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Downtown's Córdoba Cathedral, the Córdoba Cabildo, and the Plaza San Martín all serve as active public gathering spaces.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Jesuit Block (Manzana Jesuítica) is one of the most important historical and cultural landmarks in Córdoba, Argentina.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Located in the city center, it was declared a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2000 for its outstanding value as a religious, educational, and architectural complex.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Jesuits, members of the Society of Jesus founded by St.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Ignatius of Loyola in 1534, arrived in Córdoba in 1599.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] They were granted land on the southern edge of the new city, where they established a convent, cloisters, workshops, and gardens.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] In 1613, they founded the Colegio Máximo, which later developed into the National University of Córdoba, the first university in the Southern Cone and the oldest in Argentina.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Jesuit Block also became the center of a network of rural estancias (farms), which supported the order’s educational and missionary work through a model of economic self-sufficiency.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Today, parts of the Jesuit Block are open to the public, offering visitors a chance to explore Córdoba’s academic and spiritual heritage.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Highlights include the church, the historic cloisters, and the Monserrat School.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Historical Museum of the National University of Cordoba displays manuscripts, early scientific collections, and items related to the university’s history.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Guided tours often highlight underground structures and archaeological findings, adding a sense of mystery to the visit.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Jesuit Block is also connected to modern history: Pope Francis (then Jorge Mario Bergoglio) lived in Córdoba during the 1960s as a young Jesuit priest, spending a period of study and reflection in the residence linked to the complex.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Jesuit Block showcases a harmonious blend of colonial Baroque architecture and functional design rooted in Jesuit ideals of austerity and utility.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Key structures include the Iglesia de la Compañía de Jesús, built between 1640 and 1671, notable for its adobe and stone construction and wooden ceiling made using indigenous techniques.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The urban layout integrates religious, educational, and residential elements, reflecting the Jesuit commitment to community and holistic education.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The entire complex was restored following its UNESCO designation in 2000, ensuring preservation of original masonry, woodwork, and archaeological features.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Colegio Nacional de Monserrat and the residences and cloisters reflect a mix of Spanish colonial and local Criollo styles.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Underground tunnels, which likely served as ventilation and escape routes, add a layer of architectural intrigue.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Jesuit Block has had a lasting cultural, educational, and religious impact on Argentina and Latin America.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] It laid the foundation for the National University of Córdoba, the oldest in Argentina, which played a central role in the 1918 University Reform Movement that shaped higher education across Latin America.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The Jesuit system of self-sustaining rural estancias linked to the block pioneered a model of regional development.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] The site also holds spiritual significance, as it was a formative location for Pope Francis, who lived and studied there during a pivotal period in the 1960s.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Its inscription as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 2000 elevated international awareness of Jesuit cultural contributions in the Southern Cone.
[src:córdoba-argentina/córdoba-argentina] Today, the complex continues to function as a symbol of Córdoba’s academic excellence and religious heritage.
